04491nam a22005175i 9780226121956DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014003017  a97802261219567 a10.7208/97802261219562doi  a(DE-B1597)549922  a(OCoLC)890484200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPS3573.E9bA6 2014 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aWestlake, Donald E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Getaway Car :bA Donald Westlake Nonfiction Miscellany /cDonald E. Westlake; ed. by Levi Stahl. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tEditor’s Introduction -- t1 My Second Life: Fragments from an Autobiography -- t2 Donald E. Westlake, a.k.a. . . . -- t3 So Tell Me about This Job We’re Gonna Pull: On Genre -- t4 Ten Most Wanted: Ten Favorite Mystery Books -- t5 Returning to the Scene of the Crime: On His Own Work -- t6 Lunch Break: May’s Famous Tuna Casserole -- t7 The Other Guys in the String: Peers, Favorites, and Influences -- t8 Coffee Break: Letter to Ray Broekel -- t9 Anything You Say May Be Used against You: Interviews -- t10 Midnight Snack: Gustatory Notes from All Over -- t11 Side Jobs: Prison Breaks, Movie Mobsters, and Radio Comedy -- t12 Signed Confessions: Letters -- t13 Jobs Never Pulled: Title Ideas -- t14 Death Row (Or, The Happily Ever Afterlife): Letter to Ralph L. Woods -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits -- tIndex of Names and Titles0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of a fifty-year career, Donald E. Westlake published nearly one hundred books, including not one but two long-running series, starring the hard-hitting Parker and the hapless John Dortmunder. In the six years since his death, Westlake’s reputation has only grown, with fans continuing to marvel at his tightly constructed plots, no-nonsense prose, and keen, even unsettling, insights into human behavior. With The Getaway Car, we get our first glimpse of another side of Westlake the writer: what he did when he wasn’t busy making stuff up. And it’s fascinating. Setting previously published pieces, many little seen, alongside never-before-published material found in Westlake’s working files, the book offers a clear picture of the man behind the books—including his thoughts on his own work and that of his peers, mentors, and influences. The book opens with revealing (and funny) fragments from an unpublished autobiography, then goes on to offer an extended history of private eye fiction, a conversation among Westlake’s numerous pen names, letters to friends and colleagues, interviews, appreciations of fellow writers, and much, much more. There’s even a recipe for Sloth à la Dortmunder. Really. Rounded out with a foreword by Westlake’s longtime friend Lawrence Block, The Getaway Car is a fitting capstone to a storied career and a wonderful opportunity to revel anew in the voice and sensibility of a master craftsman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBlock, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlock, Lawrence.1 aStahl, Levi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStahl, Levi.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226121956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226121956.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles